  pages:
  - text: "Improvised Tourniquet\n\nField personnel are advised to fashion a tourniquet
      only when severe limb bleeding cannot be controlled by direct pressure. A strip
      of sturdy cloth (3\u20135\u202Fcm wide) and a rigid lever, such as a screwdriver
      or tent peg, suffice. Wrap the cloth two finger-breadths above the wound, knot
      once, insert the lever, twist until bleeding slows, then secure. Mark the casualty\u2019s
      forehead with a \u201CT\u201D and note the application time. Loosen briefly
      every 30\u202Fminutes to assess viability."
  - text: 'Radiation Sickness


      Symptoms may appear within hours of exposure
      to high-energy fallout: nausea, skin redness, and sudden fatigue. Initial treatment
      begins with decontamination - remove clothing, wash thoroughly with soap, and
      isolate contaminated water. If available, administer Radkiller: it is 100%
      effective at neutralizing mild radiation, but multiple doses are required in
      cases of severe exposure. Supportive care with antiemetics and electrolyte
      fluids is recommended. In the absence of lab equipment, use fever and fatigue
      as markers of immune suppression.'
  - text: "Zombie Bite Protocol\n\nThough the precise nature of zombie infection
      is not fully understood, certain field measures have shown consistent success.
      Begin by irrigating the bite wound with clean water, followed by antiseptic
      or high-proof alcohol. Splint the affected limb and monitor the patient closely.
      If signs of transformation appear - disorientation, aggression, or pale, clammy
      skin - a stabilizing compound must be administered immediately. Current protocol
      advises mixing Radkiller with a standard HealthPak. This combination has been
      shown to fully halt the infection and restore the patient\u2019s condition
      to pre-bite status, provided it is administered in time."
